      "analysis_source": "llm-per-reviewer",
      "patch_summary": "This patch set improves write performance when using the RWF_DONTCACHE flag by kicking the flusher thread for the superblock instead of initiating writeback directly. This change is based on benchmarking results that show a clear improvement over the status quo, particularly in cases with heavy write activity. The patch also includes a comparison of different IO modes for nfsd and highlights the poor performance of RWF_DONTCACHE with write-heavy workloads. The approach taken involves modifying the generic_write_sync function to kick the flusher thread, which is expected to better isolate the DONTCACHE writeback behavior and improve overall performance."
    },
    "2026-04-17": {
      "report_file": "2026-04-17_ollama_llama3.1-8b.html",
      "developer": "Jeff Layton",
      "reviews": [
        {
          "author": "Ritesh (IBM)",
          "summary": "Ritesh suggested an alternative approach to Christoph's suggestion, proposing to track the number of dontcache pages and kick the flusher for those many target pages, which would still reduce dirty page cache pressure without necessarily writing only dontcache marked folios.",
          "sentiment": "needs_work",
          "sentiment_signals": [
            "alternative approach",
            "requested implementation"
          ],
          "has_inline_review": false,
          "tags_given": [
            "Reviewed-by"
          ],
          "analysis_source": "llm",
          "raw_body": "So, if I understood it correctly, Christoph might be talking about a\ndifferent approach here.\nInstead of kicking flusher thread to writeback pages for a single inode,\nif we can track the number of dontcache pages\n(get_nr_dontcache_pages()), then we can kick the flusher for those many\ntarget pages. I think this way we are still reducing the dirty page\ncache pressure - the problem which RWF_DONTCACHE is supposed to solve.\nBut I guess, that doesn't necessarily always mean that only dontcache\nmarked folios will get written.\n\nIf we implement that then, this should still help with the batching\nproblem you mentioned and hopefully should not cause a major regression\nfor the workload which Jan mentioned.\n\nFeel free to correct my understanding here please.\n\n-ritesh",
          "reply_to": "Jeff Layton",
          "message_date": "2026-04-17",
          "message_id": "ik9qthvr.ritesh.list@gmail.com",
          "email": "ritesh.list@gmail.com",
          "is_maintainer": false
        }
      ],
      "analysis_source": "llm-per-reviewer",
      "patch_summary": "This patch set improves write performance when using the RWF_DONTCACHE flag by kicking the flusher thread for the superblock instead of initiating writeback directly. This change is based on benchmarking results that show a clear improvement over the status quo, particularly in cases with heavy write activity. The patch also includes a comparison of different IO modes for nfsd and highlights the poor performance of RWF_DONTCACHE with write-heavy workloads. The approach taken involves modifying the generic_write_sync function to kick the flusher thread, which is expected to better isolate the DONTCACHE writeback behavior and improve overall performance."
    }
